## 1. Introduction

Most of the software that powers the modern world—the servers that run websites, the tools that developers use every day, the operating systems inside supercomputers and smartphones—was not built by a single company and sold for profit. It was built openly, shared freely, and improved collectively. That is the essence of open source.

This project examines one such piece of software: LibreOffice. This report conducts a structured audit of LibreOffice across multiple dimensions: its philosophical origins, its license and ethics, its footprint on a Linux system, its place in the FOSS ecosystem, and a critical comparison with its proprietary alternatives. Alongside this report, five shell scripts demonstrate practical Linux skills that connect to the philosophy of sharing and transparency.

